Data Splitting with rsample

First, well use the rsample package to split our credit data into training and testing sets with initial_split(). Then well create data frames for the two sets.

set.seed(123)  # Setting the seed will let you reproduce a random split

# Put 3/4 of data into the training set
credit_split <- initial_split(credit_data, prop = .75)
class(credit_split)
[1] "rsplit"   "mc_split"
# Create data frames for the two sets:
train_data <- training(credit_split)
test_data <- testing(credit_split)

Create a recipe

Next, well create a recipe with the recipe() function from the recipes package. Recipes help us create and preprocess our data so its ready for modeling.

The recipe() function needs a formula and a dataset.

# Let's predict Status from all other predictors, noted by Status ~ .
credit_rec <- recipe(Status ~ ., data = credit_data)

summary(credit_rec)

But we can do more than just specify our data and formula. We can also add steps for adding, removing, or transforming our variables. We can also explicitly identify categorical variables and add dummy variables.

credit_rec <- 
  recipe(Status ~ ., data = credit_data) %>% 
  step_dummy(all_nominal(), -all_outcomes()) %>%   # Create dummy vars for all nominal vars, except outcomes
  step_corr(all_numeric(), threshold = 0.7) %>%  # remove vars with large absolute correlations w/ other vars
  step_log(Income, Expenses, Assets, Debt) %>%  # log transform vars with long right tails
  step_center(all_numeric()) %>%  # center all numeric vars
  step_zv(all_predictors())  # remove any columns with zero variance

credit_rec

Create and fit a model

Next, we need to define our model. Weve already chosen a formula (predict Status from everything) so we just need to choose the type of model and the engine, or implementation of that model that wed like to use.

In this example, well fit a logistic regression model with logistic_reg(), and well set glm as the engine. Try running show_engines("logistic_reg") to see which other options we have.

lr_mod <- 
  logistic_reg() %>% 
  set_engine("glm")

lr_mod
Logistic Regression Model Specification (classification)

Computational engine: glm

To fit the model, well first create a workflow and add our model and recipe to it.

credit_wflow <- 
  workflow() %>% 
  add_model(lr_mod) %>% 
  add_recipe(credit_rec)

credit_wflow

Finally, well call fit() from the parsnip package to fit the model. Then well use pull_workflow_fit() from workflows and tidy() from yardstick to check the results.

credit_fit <-
  credit_wflow %>% 
  fit(data = train_data)

Generate predictions for test data

Now that weve fit the model to our training data, we can apply the same trained workflow to our test data with predict().

predict(credit_fit, test_data)  # Return predicted classification

predict(credit_fit, test_data, type = "prob")  # Return probabilities

Check model performance

Lets merge these columns back into our test data and see how our model performed. We can use the roc_curve() function from the yardstick package and autoplot() from the tune package to check out the ROC curve, as well as metrics() from yardstick to check our accuracy.

credit_pred <- 
  predict(credit_fit, test_data, type = "prob") %>% 
  bind_cols(test_data) %>% 
  bind_cols(predict(credit_fit, test_data)) %>% 
  select(.pred_bad, .pred_good, .pred_class, everything())

credit_pred

credit_pred %>% 
  roc_curve(truth = Status, .pred_bad) %>% 
  autoplot()


credit_pred %>% 
  roc_auc(truth = Status, .pred_bad)

credit_pred %>% 
  metrics(truth = Status, .pred_class)

Change the model

Now that weve tried logistic regression, lets try a random forest instead.

rf_mod <- 
  rand_forest(trees = 1000) %>% 
  set_engine("ranger", num.threads = 4) %>% 
  set_mode("classification") # check show_engines("rand_forest") for all options

show_engines("rand_forest")

rf_wflow <- workflow() %>% 
  add_model(rf_mod) %>% 
  add_recipe(credit_rec)

rf_fit <- rf_wflow %>% 
  fit(data = train_data)

rf_pred <- predict(rf_fit, test_data) %>% 
  bind_cols(test_data)

rf_pred %>% 
  metrics(truth = Status, .pred_class)

Cross-validation: Now do it again! (and again, and)

set.seed(123)
cv_split <- initial_split(credit_data, .75, strata = Status)  # Stratified split on Status

cv_train <- training(cv_split)
cv_test <- testing(cv_split)

folds <- vfold_cv(cv_train, v = 10)  # 10-fold cross-validation

folds
#  10-fold cross-validation 
set.seed(456)
rf_fit_rs <-
  rf_wflow %>% 
  fit_resamples(folds)
